					<p>Ocean warming, frequent tropical cyclones, flash floods and droughts are likely to have a devastating impact on food production systems in Pacific island countries, FAO warned today. Climate change-related disasters are already imposing serious constraints on development in the islands, which appear to be in a &quot;constant mode of recovery,&quot; according to a new report entitled Climate Change and Food Security in Pacific Island Countries. (Sources: FAO, 2 December 2008).</p>
